      <body>
         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne bot garden ¶ 1/12/71. ¶  ¶ Since I wrote last, dear Dr Hooker, I was able to secure yet for the Niagara stems of ¶  ¶ Dicksonia squarrosa ¶  ¶ Cyathea dealbata [&amp;]...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">71.12.01c</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1871-81, ff. 27-8 </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Melbourne bot garden</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">1/12/71.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Since I wrote last, dear Dr Hooker, I was able to secure yet for the Niagara stems of</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Dicksonia%20squarrosa">Dicksonia squarrosa</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Cyathea%20dealbata">Cyathea dealbata</name> [&amp;]</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Cyathea%20Smithii">Cyathea Smithii</name>,</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">of which you can have one stem of each for Kew and one for Mr Booth of Flottbeck, if you desire it.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See M to J. Hooker, 5 November 1871.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>You will also get by the Niagara <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">gigantic</hi>
               </seg> stems of <name key="Dicksonia%20antarctica">Dicksonia antarctica</name> and one very tall one of <name key="Alsophila%20Australis">Alsophila Australis</name>, if you value them for Kew or Flottbeck.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The Captain of the Niagra<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Niagara.</p>
               </note> has fine accommodation for these stems and will water them on the voyage. He retains some himself for the owners of the ship, and the rest of these ferns got thus a free passage. You are entitled to select the largest specimens.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Lately the large <name key="Iridea">Iridea</name> of Lord Howe's Island has flowered. It proves a new Iris of the section Moraea, which I have named Iris (Moraea) Robinsonii in honor of my friend Sir Hercules Robinson, the Governor of Ceylon, who is promoted lately to the Governor Ship of N.S. Wales. Hence this Iris belongs to his territory now. It is in flower much like <name key="Iris%20compressa">Iris compressa</name> Thunb., on which Linné founded his genus Moraea, but the leaves and stem are as large as that of <name key="Phormium">Phormium</name>! To me it seems clear, That Kers &amp; Endlichers genus Moraea, (but not Thunbergs) must fall together with Iris, by which means we obtain a very natural genus, ranging still wider then <name key="Sisyrinchium">Sisyrinchium</name>.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M named <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Iris robinsoniana</seg> in B71.12.03, p. 153-4, citing it also as <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Moraea robinsoniana</seg> under the joint authority of himself and Charles Moore. Bentham (1863-78) vol. <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>6, p. 409, rejected M's uniting <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Moraea</seg> with <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Iris</seg>, and listed it <seg style="font-style: italic; ">as M. robinsoniana</seg>.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Klatts notes on the S. African <name key="Iridea">Iridea</name>e<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Probably in the series of papers in <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Linnaea</seg> culminating in Klatt (1866). In B65.10.01, p. 21, M records having volumes of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Linnaea</seg> only for 1847–57.</p>
               </note> I have not yet seen. Our late lamented friend, Prof Harvey, never likely entering on a comparison of Iris &amp; Moraea, keeps in your edition of his genera only Moraea up.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Harvey (1868), p. 372.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have established also a new genus of <name key="Saxifrageae">Saxifrageae</name> from Lord Howes Island, namely <name key="Colmeiroa">Colmeiroa</name>,<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M erected <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Colmeiroa">Colmeiroa</name>
                     </seg> (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">C. carpodetoides</seg>), in B71.12.03, p. 149.</p>
               </note> next to <name key="Carpodetus">Carpodetus</name>, but the cells are one seeded, &amp; it is differing also in some other respect <name key="Colmeiroa">Colmeiroa</name> of Reuter is not upheld by [J] Müller as you know.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Reuter's genus <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Colmeiroa">Colmeiroa</name>
                     </seg> (Euphorbiaceae) was established in 1843, but J. Müller (1866), p. 448, treated it as a synonym of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Fluggeae</seg>, erected in 1805.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>There are several other plants from Ld Howes Island, which I have examined for the current number of the Fragmenta, which is to appear this month.<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B71.12.03.</p>
               </note> But what is this to the treasures of the wonderland New Guinea!</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>For the first time since 1847, I have no letters by mail from Europe through the sinking of the Rangoon at Ceylon.<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Rangoon</seg> struck a rock while leaving Galle Harbour, Ceylon, on 1 November: 'All lives were saved, but the whole of the Australian mails, the cargo and the passengers' baggage were lost' (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">Argus</seg>, 27 November 1871 p. 5).</p>
               </note> I trust, that all my friends &amp; correspondents will repeat in their next months letter, what they wrote &amp; send duplicates of any prints lost with the wreck at Point d[e] Gall[e].</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Possibly Mr Bentham may have written to obtain new material; so he must kindly repeat his wishes.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The loss of Sir Rod. Murchison is a sad one to Geography &amp; Geology.<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Murchison died on 22 October 1871.</p>
               </note> To me he always proved a kind condescending friend. I wished he could have lived to see Livingstone return, if indeed that brave man will really ever see civilisation again.<note xml:id="ftn11" type="footnote" n="11">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See Murchison (1864-5): the Royal Geographical Society had engaged Livingstone 'once more to revisit Southeastern Africa, and determine the hidden watershed of that vast country' (p. 249) where, 'in addition to his efforts as a Geographer [he] … will act as a pioneer in removing those obstacles which at present render the traveling of Christian missionaries … fraught with disaster and profitless suffering' (p. 264). Livingstone was still in the field at the time M wrote (see Livingstone's 1871 field diary, http://livingstone.library.ucla.edu/1871diary/index.htm, accessed 18 January 2014).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Always yr</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">The Captain has 2 tall Alsophilas from me. Perhaps he would spare one for Mr Booth, and take an other Dicksonia </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The Australian Eclipse Expedition may bring a few new plants from Cape Sidmouth.<note xml:id="ftn12" type="footnote" n="12">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>A total solar eclipse occurred in the far north of Australia on 11 December 1871. The Sydney and Melbourne Observatories collaborated in sending a party to Torres Strait to view the event.</p>
               </note> I am promoting also, indeed called forth Mr Giles Expedition from the S. Austr telegraph line to West Australia, probably the River Murchison.<note xml:id="ftn13" type="footnote" n="13">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Giles's 1872 expedition from 23 August to 18 November 1872 was blocked by lack of water and the salt pans of Lake Amadeus. See B75.04.07 and Giles (1875).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
